## Recommended: Use `System.IO.Abstractions`

This is a battle-tested NuGet package purpose-built for your scenario — no need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool FolderExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.True(service.FolderExists("/data"));
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Load("/data/config.json"));

service.Save("/data/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.txt"));
```

### Why this over a custom wrapper?

| | Custom `IFileSystem` | `System.IO.Abstractions` |
|---|---|---|
| Coverage | Only what you wrap | Full `System.IO` surface |
| Maintenance | You own it | Community-maintained |
| Test helpers | Write your own mock | `MockFileSystem` included |

The key migration steps: replace `using System.IO;` calls with calls on the injected `IFileSystem`, then use `MockFileSystem` in tests. If you'd like help bulk-migrating the call sites, let me know.
